title: SFH on human swine flu (with photo)
content_text:
p>
Following is the transcript of remarks made by the Secretary for Food and 
Health, Dr York Chow, and the Controller of the Centre for Health 
Protection, Dr Thomas Tsang at a stand-up media session at Legislative 
Council Building today (May 11): Reporter: How concerned are you about the latest case concerning the 
Northwest flight, and also if China confirmed the first case, what sort of 
measures will Hong Kong take? Secretary for Food and Health: We are always concerned about patients who 
might carry the virus to Hong Kong, whether those contacts can be traced

might carry the virus to Hong Kong, whether those contacts can be traced 
early, whether they can be identified and placed under quarantine or medical 
surveillance. So, every case that might have such implication will concern 
us. Just remember the last weekend, regarding the three Japanese cases, we 
have worked very hard in order to trace all the people who have been in 
contact with the Japanese patients, who came to Hong Kong either directly or 
indirectly. We have already identified the two close contacts. We were able

indirectly. We have already identified the two close contacts. We were able 
to place them under quarantine and they have been tested negative for the 
virus so far. We are still undergoing tests for the rest of the contacts, 
and most of them are already put into hospitals for testing and quarantine. 
We believe that this particular episode has allowed us to work very closely 
following our guidelines. So for every case that might have such suspicion, 
we have already started working, and once it is confirmed, then of course we

we have already started working, and once it is confirmed, then of course we 
will make sure that work is being done. Reporter: How about the China case, if it is confirmed? Secretary for Food and Health: Once it is confirmed, we will start tracing 
those people who might actually pass through Hong Kong. Once we got the name 
list, the Immigration Department will check whether they have passed through 
Hong Kong, whether they have entered Hong Kong, or just arrived in Hong Kong 
airport as a transit passenger and so on, we need to do that once it is

airport as a transit passenger and so on, we need to do that once it is 
confirmed. Reporter: Dr Tsang, can I assume that you are still trying to look for one 
passenger. You have already located 11, but one is still missing, right? Controller of the Centre for Health Protection: I think you mean the 
passengers from the NW 025, we are still looking for two passengers, whom we 
do not have concrete information about. Of the rest, I mean the other 17, we

have either already located them, or referred them to hospital, or put them 
under medical surveillance. Reporter: What about the two unaccountable guests from Metro Park, have you 
ever found them? Controller of the Centre for Health Protection: I think we have not located 
them at this point.  Reporter: Are you concerned? Controller of the Centre for Health Protection: I am not particularly 
concerned because the incubation period is already over and the quarantine 
has been lifted. And all the other residents and guests in the hotel, they

has been lifted. And all the other residents and guests in the hotel, they 
are free from the infection. So I think the risks posed by these two persons 
are really not very high. Reporter: Mr Secretary, can I just ask you why don't you just follow Beijing 
and be very tough on western visitors and especially those from North 
America? Secretary for Food and Health: As you know that, people coming from Mexico 
or anywhere in North America, they do not necessarily come directly from 
those cities to Hong Kong. Most of them might have stopped over in Asian

those cities to Hong Kong. Most of them might have stopped over in Asian 
cities as well. So I do not think you can impose such a widespread 
travelling ban on people coming to Hong Kong without a good scientific 
evidence. It is important for us to give clear information to them to report 
any sickness. At the same time, we have a series of protection that we have 
instilled at our borders, including health declaration, thermal screening. 
And those people working in the Immigration Department will also look at

And those people working in the Immigration Department will also look at 
various passengers, enquire where they come from, and be able to inform them 
about the risk of transmitting diseases. So it is not just one single policy 
that is effective. It is a series of multiple policies coming together that 
can protect us. So I need to stress again, we cannot just rely on one single 
measure, we have to rely on these groups of measures, so that we can ensure 
Hong Kong is still safe. And even if we have imported case, we hope that we

Hong Kong is still safe. And even if we have imported case, we hope that we can detect it early so that we can contain it as much as we can. At the moment, this is still our objective. (Please also refer to the Chinese session of the transcript)
